Hi guys

Driving a car with COE expiring 2023. Based on sgcarmart my car model and age would sell for about 21-22k on the used market. Planning to sell it off and move to public transport as I am changing jobs to somewhere that is accessible by a <$2 bus ride each way. Loan balance is about $10k or slightly less.

Can I seek advice on which are the best ways of selling off my car to get the best selling price? I have researched and come across the following ways:

1. Carousell. But the people who respond are mostly dealers who want me to sell to them, or want me to let them sell for me. I have had offers of about $16k but I am waiting for something more.

2. Dealer to sell for me on consignment basis. I am aware that most dealers charge a commission for this but I don't know how much. I have heard that it ranges from $100 to a specific percentage of the selling price.

3. Direct Owner advert on sgcarmart. The website offers about $58 for an advert, which is online until the car is sold. This lets me reach out to direct buyers and can nego without dealers. Potentially I think this way can get me the best price for my car, even if I choose to sell it below the dealers' market price, for e.g. sell at $18k ot $19k is better for the buyer than paying $21k.

4. Sell to dealer directly. But I am sure they want a cut of the profits as well and this would mean I am taking the lowest price possible for my car. I would expect to get only $15k or less if I choose this method.

5. Scrap and recover the unused portion of COE. This is the least preferred way as I only get back about $10k which means nothing in my pocket after paying off the loan.

Thanks for reading and hope I can get some useful advice from experienced forumers here.

1. Why would you want to go Carousel? Because most of the time, things are the cheapest there right? Hence if you advertise by Carousel, you will get lowballing enquiries. Period.

2. I wouldn't recommend consigning. There are many hidden T&Cs from these dealers even though it might be of no costs to you. Case in point, I put up my 22mth old A3 4 yrs ago for sale via a consignment dealer. Took me 12 mths to offload at a 10K difference in asking price. The main reason why there were so few buyers made known to me is because they need to pay 2K in "admin charges" to the consignment dealer. It was never made known to me in the first place and I didn't know until a buyer agree to those terms, come view my car, and told me about it. So I wouldn't recommend this route; like seriously.

3. I just did that with my car 2 weeks ago. Sold within 3 days to the first viewer. with 3 more guys on the waiting list to view. As long as your car is in good or at least reasonable condition and your expectant pricing is realistic, it will move. In-between, there will be tons of dealers calling to lowball you. Some of them cannot understand simple English even if you indicated NO DEALERS NO CONSIGNMENT PLS. Resist the temptation to feel demoralized and dejected. Even though your sgcarmart advert is perpetual, set yourself a baseline minimum and a timeline to offload the car; and to take the listing completely off. The longer it appears in the ad, the more your buyers will know you are stuck with it and will continue to lowball you.

4. Dealers do not owe you a living. They need to survive. They call you Bro to get your sympathy; not to be your friend. Remember neither do you owe them a living too.

5. Only if your car is left < 1yr lifespan. Else don't even think of it.

Just sharing which I sold my kimchi ride which left 4 months coe.

Try out carosuell initially, many dealers and low ballers. But got one direct buyer came to view the car and everything was good. Wanted to deposit on first meetup but pending send to his ws for inspection. Fixed a date 1 mth later but deal was called off.

One month later try out sgcarmart, within 3 days someone came to view and deposit the car. Was a direct buyer and within 2 weeks everything settle thru cash and paperwork use sgcarmart form. Everything done ourself.

Concurrently brought a preowned car from caroseull from direct seller.
Only ask for $500 discount from his asking price. Ownself do paperwork was a smooth transaction.

U can try caroseull first, then set a timeline about 2-3 weeks of no people buy then go sgcarmart.

But prepare sgcarmart u advertise , many phone calls and WhatsApp.

knightcover said:
How do you tell if the "buyer" is a real buyer or a dealer? Appreciate your inputs!

Sent from Daenerys of the House Targaryen, the First of Her Name, The Unburnt, Queen of the Andals, the Rhoynar and the First Men, Queen of Meereen, Khaleesi of the Great Grass Sea, Protector of the Realm, Lady Regent of the Seven Kingdoms, Breaker of Chains and Mother of Dragons. using GAGT

Few tell tale signs:

1. Mobile numbers. Just like Property agents, some car dealers have nice mobile numbers. 9800 3500 or 9005 9006 u know this kinda of pattern? You see it, you know this guy bidded the number to make it easy for his customers to remember

2. Offers that gets thrown at you over an SMS or WA; even before any viewing is done. And more often than not, these are lowballing figures. If you receive one, 199% its dealer. I have not met any fellow countrymen willing to throw an offer without testing, let alone viewing

3. T & Cs that have telltale signs that suggest the transaction will be between you, and a company (business entity). Sometimes you can pick this up from the simple conversation. No dealers will want to register under their own name. It increases the ownership transfer counts and decreases the selling appeal to other buyers.

Having said that, I do agree that you might only know that the guy is a dealer or broker only at the point of transfer. But let's be honest. If you reach this far in the process, you probably gotten the price you want. Get it done, transferred, take the cash, move on. If the dealer resell this at a higher price, it means they are good enough to do so. They are able to offer value added service such as full loan, or full touchup/repair at low costs prior to handing over the car to the next buyer. In any case, all risks on them to find a willing buyer meet their asking price. None of your biz anymore. Don't fret or sulk over it.

I just wan to add-on on the consignment part again. When you go consignment part, the attractive part is the dealer will advertise for you across all platforms at their costs. But this is also the downside! Because if your car doesn't move and you wana self advert, you can't. Each site only allows 1 registration for the same car plate number (maybe not so for carousel but sgcarmart confirmed won't allow it). Hence its like hooking you onto drugs. You fall into this; either you sell the car through them at their terms or you back out of the deal at the costs they penalize you for. That is why I strongly discourage going via Cgnmt route if you can.

One more tip for you. Anyone who responded to you have the courtesy to inform them that any offers below a certain threshold, you would appreciate that they don't make the trip down to view your car. For example, recently I advert my Civic for sale. My advert was 48K while the mkt rate was going at 42 ~ 44K. In my messages to viewers who responded, I made it very clear that any offers in the 30s regions please refrain from making the trip. Nice way to put it: I don't want to waste your time and effort to come all the way. Of course the true intent is not to waste MY time and petrol for test drive. Reality hurts but you need to protect your own interest. You need to limit abuses to your car unless, your intent is to flaunt off the performance of the car then that is another matter altogether.

Chinese has a saying: 1 kind of rice, feeds 100 kinds of people. Expect all kinds of buyers, inquiries and requests. The most recent one I had with my car was a financial advisor guy trying to get up close and personal with me to sell his products. The car buying inquiry was a cover for that move; given all the recent ** measures. That guy really takes product selling to the next level!
